H0.text: Plant cells are distinguished by the presence of a cell wall, a large central vacuole, and organelles called plastids.

H1.text: Animal cells are distinguished by the presence of a cell wall, a large central vacuole, and organelles called plastids.

H2.text: Reproductive cells are distinguished by the presence of a cell wall, a large central vacuole, and organelles called plastids.

H3.text: Heterotrophs are cells that have a cell wall, a large central vacuole, and organelles called plastids.

A4.text: Plant cells have cell walls composed of cellulose, hemicelluloses, and pectin.

A5.text: Many types of plant cells contain a large central vacuole, a water-filled volume enclosed by a membrane known as the tonoplast.
